{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 15:09:42.259490", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis — summary and findings\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall the customer-facing network (hosts in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) and the server/service plane (10.200.0.0/24) are healthy: hosts can reach DNS (10.200.0.2), the DHCP server (10.200.0.8), the load-balancer (10.200.0.7) and the public web servers (10.200.0.3–.6). OSPF routes for the 10.* subnets are present on core/distribution/server-access routers.\\n- A clear, consistent abnormality: addresses in the backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2) are unreachable from the client host subnets and from many other nodes in the network (multiple ping sources show status \"unknown\" to 20.200.0.x). Backend nodes can talk to each other and to the load-balancer, but the rest of the network has no route to 20.200.0.0/24.\\n- Root cause (localized): the 20.200.0.0/24 backend network is not being advertised (no OSPF route) into the wider OSPF domain — it exists only locally on the hosts that are directly connected (load_balancer and backends). In other words, the backend network is isolated from OSPF and thus from the client subnets and most servers/routers.\\n\\nEvidence and relevant data (selected)\\n1) Reachability summary (extracted from the aggregated ping results)\\n- Pings from many client hosts to 10.200.0.* and to the load_balancer (10.200.0.7) are OK (0% loss).\\n- Pings from client hosts to backend addresses 20.200.0.2–20.200.0.4 are consistently \"unknown\" (no results), e.g. many entries in the reachability output show status \"unknown\" for backend_web_0/1/2 when source is client hosts.\\n- Backend nodes can ping each other and the load-balancer (backend_web_1 -> backend_web_2, backend_web_0 -> backend_web_1, backend_web_* -> load_balancer are OK).\\n\\n2) Router route tables (selected)\\n- server_access_router (running FRR) routing table (showing OSPF routes):\\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0 (present).\\n  - No 20.200.0.0/24 route appears in the server_access_router route table.\\n- router_core_1 / router_core_2 / router_core_3 OSPF tables:\\n  - All show OSPF routes for client 10.* subnets and 10.200.0.0/24.\\n  - No entry for 20.200.0.0/24 is present on the core routers\\' routing tables.\\n\\n3) Load-balancer host configuration (load_balancer)\\n- load_balancer has:\\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (public/service-facing)\\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (backend-facing)\\n- Its routing table shows 20.200.0.0/24 is directly connected via eth1 and default route via 10.200.0.1 (server_access_router).\\n- There is no indication the load_balancer is advertising 20.200.0.0/24 into OSPF (it appears not to be an OSPF-speaking router).\\n\\nLocalization — which devices/networks are involved\\n- Affected network: 20.200.0.0/24 (backend web subnet).\\n- Devices that have the 20.200.0.0/24 network attached: load_balancer (20.200.0.1) and backend_web_0..2 (20.200.0.2–4).\\n- Devices that do not know this network (lack routes): server_access_router and the core routers (router_core_1/2/3) — their FRR OSPF tables do not contain 20.200.0.0/24.\\n- Functional connectivity inside backend: the backend hosts and load_balancer are mutually reachable (local connectivity OK).\\n\\nProbable root cause (concise)\\n- The 20.200.0.0/24 backend subnet is not being advertised into OSPF (or otherwise routed) across the enterprise routing domain. As a result, devices outside the backend segment (client hosts, many servers, and core routers) do not have a route to 20.200.0.0/24 and cannot reach those IPs directly.\\n- Contributing detail: load_balancer and backend hosts hold addresses in 20.200.0.0/24 and are reachable among themselves, but the load_balancer does not appear to be injecting that connected network into FRR/OSPF (and server_access_router has no static/OSPF route to 20.200.0.0/24). This isolates the backend subnet from the rest of the OSPF domain.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Clients and normal traffic are able to access published services through the load-balancer (10.200.0.7) and can reach the public web servers (10.200.0.3–.6) and DNS/DHCP; user-facing functionality (resolving and reaching web99.local via 10.200 web addresses) should operate normally.\\n- Direct access to backend servers at 20.200.0.0/24 from clients and most routers is not possible (expected if intentionally isolated — see note below). Any tools, monitoring, or management that assume reachability of 20.200.0.0/24 from other network segments will fail.\\n- Internal backend connectivity (backend <-> backend and backend <-> load_balancer) is intact.\\n\\nNotes and observations\\n- The initial network description stated \"by design the backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts.\" The observed lack of reachability from hosts to 20.200.0.0/24 matches that design intent. However, the description also said \"All infrastructure and server networks are advertised by FRR OSPF so that hosts can resolve and access the web services end-to-end.\" If that latter statement is strict, there is a discrepancy: 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in OSPF tables and therefore not advertised network-wide.\\n- Some RTTs to certain leaf web servers occasionally show high variance — there are a few instances of elevated rtt_max/mdev to 10.200.0.5 and 10.200.0.6 from some hosts. These are intermittent and not widespread packet-loss events; they may warrant additional observation if performance problems are reported, but they are secondary compared to the backend advertisement issue.\\n- Backend nodes have local connectivity and can reach the load_balancer, which is the intended access point for clients to reach backend-hosted services.\\n\\nSummary conclusion\\n- Network is broadly healthy for client-to-public-service traffic (10.200.*) and infrastructure services (DNS/DHCP/load-balancer).\\n- The backend subnet 20.200.0.0/24 is isolated from the enterprise OSPF domain (no OSPF route present on server_access_router or core routers). The likely root cause is that the backend network is not being advertised into OSPF (or otherwise routed) — the devices holding that subnet (load_balancer + backend_web hosts) are not injecting it into FRR/OSPF or server_access_router has no route pointing toward the backend segment.\\n- Localization: the issue is centered on the backend network segment and the interaction (or lack thereof) between the load_balancer/backend hosts and the server_access_router/FRR OSPF domain.\\n\\nIf you want, I can (next step, upon request) run targeted checks to confirm which device lacks OSPF advertisement (e.g., inspect FRR OSPF config on server_access_router, check OSPF neighbors, or query load_balancer for routing/OSPF/daemon status). For now I have not performed any configuration changes or applied mitigations., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='d19ddf0a-3a3b-4768-9239-19956448bcb6'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
